Assumptions for anova

Condensing to mean

The mixed effect anova will needs a dataframe with one rt per subject, per congruency, per IOS.

d <- df %>% 
  group_by(subject, congruency, IOS) %>% 
  summarise_at(vars(rt), list(rt = mean)) %>% 
  ungroup()

Outliers

d %>% 
  group_by(congruency, IOS) %>%
  identify_outliers(rt)
## # A tibble: 1 x 6
##   congruency IOS   subject    rt is.outlier is.extreme
##   <fct>      <ord> <fct>   <dbl> <lgl>      <lgl>     
## 1 congruent  3     53259   0.307 TRUE       FALSE

1 outlier is found, it is not extreme. Not an issue, we will leave it in. (outliers have been removed in Data_cleaning.Rmd with MAD method)

Homogneity of variance assumption

d %>%
  group_by(congruency) %>%
  levene_test(rt ~ IOS)
## # A tibble: 2 x 5
##   congruency    df1   df2 statistic     p
##   <fct>       <int> <int>     <dbl> <dbl>
## 1 incongruent     4     5     0.530 0.721
## 2 congruent       4     5     0.276 0.882

Somehow, there is homogeneity of variances

Homogeneity of covariances assumption

box_m(d[, "rt", drop = FALSE], d$IOS)
## # A tibble: 1 x 4
##   statistic p.value parameter method                                            
##       <dbl>   <dbl>     <dbl> <chr>                                             
## 1      1.05   0.903         4 Box's M-test for Homogeneity of Covariance Matric

Were good again!

Assumption of sphericity

Included in the test

Mixed anova

# Two-way mixed ANOVA test
res.aov <- 
  anova_test(data = d,
  dv = rt, wid = subject,
  between = IOS, within = congruency
  )
get_anova_table(res.aov)
## ANOVA Table (type III tests)
## 
##           Effect DFn DFd      F     p p<.05   ges
## 1            IOS   4   5  0.670 0.640       0.337
## 2     congruency   1   5 18.571 0.008     * 0.164
## 3 IOS:congruency   4   5  0.832 0.558       0.034

Post hoc

d %>%
  pairwise_t_test(
    rt ~ congruency, paired = TRUE, 
    p.adjust.method = "bonferroni"
  )
